  "prompt": "Is drinking a compulsion in the Indian Army? What if one chooses not to drink?",
  "response": "In the Indian Army, like in many military organizations, there is a culture that can sometimes involve social drinking. However, drinking is not a compulsion, and individuals are free to choose whether or not to consume alcohol. The Indian Army emphasizes discipline, fitness, and personal responsibility, and there are clear regulations regarding alcohol consumption, especially during duty hours or in operational areas.\n\nIf an individual chooses not to drink, it is perfectly acceptable, and there is no pressure to do so. The Army respects personal choices and values the discipline and professionalism of its personnel above all else. Many soldiers and officers abstain from alcohol for personal, religious, or health reasons, and this has no negative impact on their career or standing within the organization.\n\nIt's important to note that excessive or irresponsible drinking is discouraged and can lead to disciplinary action, as it can compromise operational readiness and safety. The Indian Army encourages a healthy and balanced lifestyle, and individuals who choose not to drink are fully supported in their decision.",
